ikely' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=2 March 2020 |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n*3 March \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The government publishes its action plan for dealing with coronavirus. This includes scenarios ranging from a milder pandemic to a \"severe prolonged pandemic [[Spanish flu|as experienced in 1918]]\" and warns that a fifth of the national workforce could be absent from work during the infection's peak.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51718917 |title=Coronavirus: Up to fifth of UK workers 'off sick at same time' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=3 March 2020 |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/03/uk-government-coronavirus-plans-strip-fire-and-police-to-essentials-covid-19 |title=UK coronavirus plans would strip police and fire services to essentials |work=The Guardian|date=3 March 2020 |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n*5 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The airline [[Flybe]] collapses into administration, due in part to the impact of the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51746564 |title=Collapsed Flybe tells passengers not to travel to airports |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The first death from coronavirus in the UK is confirmed,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51759602 |title=Coronavirus: Older patient becomes first virus fatality in UK |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC News |date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref> as the number of cases exceeds 100, with a total of 115 having tested positive. England's [[Chief Medical Officer (United Kingdom)|Chief Medical Officer]], [[Chris Whitty]], tells MPs that the UK has now moved to the second stage of dealing with COVID-19 \u2013 from \"containment\" to the \"delay\" phase.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/05/more-than-a-hundred-people-in-uk-infected-with-coronavirus |title=More than a hundred people in UK infected with coronavirus |work=The Guardian|date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n*6 March \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The Prime Minister announces \u00a346 million in funding for research into a coronavirus vaccine and rapid diagnostic tests. During a visit to a laboratory in Bedfordshire, he says: \"It looks like there will be a substantial period of disruption where we have to deal with this outbreak.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/mar/06/coronavirus-update-latest-live-news-symptoms-cases-global-infection-rate-uk-usa-australia-italy-china-updates?page=with:block-5e624ca98f087df56e4c37f9#block-5e624ca98f087df56e4c37f9 |title=Coronavirus latest updates |work=The Guardian|date=6 March 2020 |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n*8 March \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: A third death from coronavirus is reported, at [[North Manchester General Hospital]], as the number of cases in the UK reaches 273, the largest single-day increase so far.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51796072 |title=Coronavirus: Man in his 60s becomes third UK death |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=8 March 2020 |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n*9 March \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The [[FTSE 100]] plunges by more than 8 percent, its largest intraday fall since 2008, amid concerns over the spread of COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cityam.com/coronavirus-ftse-100-plunges-on-open-after-oil-prices-crash-30-per-cent/ |title=Coronavirus: FTSE 100 plunges after oil prices crash 30 per cent |work=City AM |publisher=City AM |date=9 March 2020 |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n*10 March \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Health minister [[Nadine Dorries]] tests positive for coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51827356 |title=Coronavirus: Health minister Nadine Dorries tests positive |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=10 March 2020 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*11 March\n**The [[Bank of England]] cuts its baseline interest rate from 0.75% to 0.25%, back down to the lowest level in history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51831004 |title=UK interest rates cut in emergency move |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], [[Rishi Sunak]], presents the Johnson Government's [[March 2020 United Kingdom budget|first budget]], which includes \u00a330 billion in measures to protect the economy from coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-budget/uk-pledges-30-billion-to-protect-economy-from-coronavirus-idUKKBN20Y007 |title=UK pledges \u00a330 billion to protect economy from coronavirus |work=Reuters |publisher=Reuters |date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51835306 |title=Budget 2020: Chancellor unveils \u00a330bn coronavirus package |work=BBC News|publisher=BBC News|date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/11/key-points-from-budget-2020-at-a-glance |title=Key points from budget 2020 \u2013 at a glance |work=The Guardian|date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*12 March \u2013 Following a series of recent major falls, the FTSE100 plunges yet again, this time by over 10%, its biggest drop since 1987.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51829852 |title=Coronavirus: Global stocks plunge as coronavirus fears spread |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/live/2020/mar/12/stock-markets-tumble-trump-europe-travel-ban-ecb-christine-lagarde-business-live?page=with:block-5e6a636e8f08c2df6d278620#block-5e6a636e8f08c2df6d278620 |title=FTSE 100 suffers second worst day ever after 10.87% plunge \u2013 business live |work=The Guardian|date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref> Other markets around the world are similarly affected by ongoing economic turmoil.\n*13 March \n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The [[Premier League]] [[2019\u201320 Premier League|2019\u20132020 season]] is suspended, amid a growing list of worldwide sporting cancellations and postponements due to COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51867989 |title=Coronavirus: Premier League and EFL suspended until 3 April at earliest |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Elections including the [[2020 United Kingdom local elections|English local elections]], [[2020 London mayoral election|London mayoral election]] and [[2020 England and Wales police and crime commissioner elections|police and crime commissioner elections]], scheduled for May 2020, are postponed for a year because of the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51876269 |title=Coronavirus: English local elections postponed for a year |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n*14 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: A further 10 people are reported to have died from COVID-19, almost doubling the UK death toll from 11 to 21. The government's aim for a \"[[herd immunity]]\" approach generates controversy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/health/uk-herd-immunity-coronavirus-who-margaret-harris-a4387346.html |title=UK's 'herd immunity' approach to tackling coronavirus questioned by World Health Organisation |work=Evening Standard|date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-51892402 |title=Coronavirus: Scientists say UK virus strategy is 'risking lives' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC News |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://maths.qmul.ac.uk/~vnicosia/UK_scientists_statement_on_coronavirus_measures.pdf |title=Public request to take stronger measures of socialdistancing across the UK with immediate effect |work=Queen Mary University of London |publisher=Queen Mary University of London |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[Vice President of the United States]], [[Mike Pence]], announces the US is to extend its European [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States#Travel and entry restrictions|coronavirus travel ban]] to include the UK from 16 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-51891662 |title=Coronavirus: US to extend travel ban to UK and Ireland |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: UK retailers release a joint letter asking customers not to panic buy products after some supermarkets sell out of items such as pasta, hand gel and toilet paper.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51883440 |title=Coronavirus: Supermarkets ask shoppers to be 'considerate' and stop panic buying |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n*15 March \n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]] advises against \"all but essential travel\" to the US.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/mar/15/coronavirus-latest-updates-trump-tests-negative-as-spain-orders-nationwide-lockdown-uk-us-australia-italy-europe-global-economy?page=with:block-5e6e17e48f088d7575593aed#block-5e6e17e48f088d7575593aed |title=UK advises against 'all but essential' travel to US |work=The Guardian|date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Health Secretary [[Matt Hancock]] says that every UK resident over the age of 70 will be told \"within the coming weeks\" to self-isolate for \"a very long time\" to shield them from coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51895873 |title=Coronavirus: Isolation for over-70s 'within weeks' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The government announces plans to hold daily televised press conferences to update the public on the fight against the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|coronavirus pandemic]], starting on Monday 16 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51901818 |title=Coronavirus: Downing Street to give daily update on fight against outbreak |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n*16 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]:  The UK death toll from the coronavirus pandemic reaches 55, with the number of cases of the illness passing 1,500.<ref name=avoid>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51917562 |title=Coronavirus: PM says everyone should avoid office, pubs and travelling |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Prime Minister Boris Johnson advises everyone in the UK against \"non-essential\" travel and contact with others to curb coronavirus, as well as suggesting people should avoid pubs, clubs and theatres, and work from home if possible. Pregnant women, people over the age of 70 and those with certain health conditions are urged to consider the advice \"particularly important\", and will be asked to self-isolate within days.<ref name=avoid/>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The BBC delays its planned changes to TV licences for the over-75s from June to August because of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51911065 |title=Coronavirus: BBC delays over-75 TV licence fee changes |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n*17 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: NHS England announces that all non-urgent operations in England will be postponed from 15 April to free up 30,000 beds to help tackle the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51933410 |title=Coronavirus: All non-urgent operations in England postponed |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Hashem Abedi, brother of [[Manchester Arena bombing|Manchester Arena bomber]] [[Salman Abedi]], is found guilty of murdering 22 people in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-51926162 |title=Manchester Arena bombing: Hashem Abedi guilty of 22 murders |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The Chancellor, Rishi Sunak, announces that \u00a3330bn will be made available in loan guarantees for businesses affected by the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/mar/17/boris-johnson-coronavirus-press-conference-rishi-sunak-cabinet-as-rishi-sunak-set-to-announcing-coronavirus-financial-rescue-package-politics-live?page=with:block-5e71052d8f088d757559527b#block-5e71052d8f088d757559527b |title=Sunak says he will make \u00a3330bn available in lending to keep firms in business |work=The Guardian|date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51935467 |title=Coronavirus: Chancellor unveils \u00a3330bn lifeline for economy |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The UK coronavirus-related death toll rises to 71, while the number of confirmed cases of the illness rises to 1,950.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jane |last=Dalton |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/uk-coronavirus-death-toll-nhs-latest-outbreak-pandemic-a9407311.html |title=UK coronavirus death toll rises to 71 |publisher=Independent Print Limited |newspaper=The Independent |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/