{"title_page": "Ron Toomer", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Ron Toomer\n| image       =\n| alt         =\n| caption     =\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1930|05|31}}\n| birth_place = Pasadena, California\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|2011|09|26|1930|05|31}}\n| death_place = Bedford, Texas\n| nationality =\n| other_names =\n| known_for   = Arrow Dynamics\n| occupation  = Roller coaster designer\n}}\n'''Ronald Valentine Toomer''' (May 31, 1930&nbsp;\u2013 September 26, 2011)<ref>[http://www.amusementtoday.com/2011/09/26/industry-legend-ron-toomer-dies-at-81/ Industry legend Ron Toomer dies at 81]</ref> was an American [[roller coaster]] designer credited for designing 93 roller coasters around the world.<ref name=AT>{{Citation | last = Rutherford | first = Scott | title = Industry legend, roller coaster designer Ton Toomer dies at 81 | journal = Amusement Today | volume = 15 | issue = 8.1  | pages = 33\u201335  | date = November 2011}}</ref> He graduated from the [[University of Nevada, Reno]] in 1961 with a degree in mechanical engineering and was a part of the design team responsible for the [[Apollo program|Apollo]] spacecraft heat shield.<ref name=AT/>\n\n== Career ==\nRon Toomer was hired by [[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow Development]] founders Karl Bacon and Ed Morgan in 1965 to help design a mine train ride called [[Runaway Mine Train (Six Flags Over Texas)|Run-A-Way Mine Train]] at [[Six Flags Over Texas]].<ref name=AN>{{Citation | last = Seifert | first = Jeffrey | title = Ron Toomer 1930-2011  | journal = ACE News | volume = 24 | issue = 2 | page = 3 | date = December 2011}}</ref> It opened in 1966 utilizing the tubular steel rail technology that had been developed by Arrow for [[Disneyland]]'s [[Matterhorn Bobsleds]]. The concept caught on quickly and Toomer designed 15 more mine train coasters for Arrow. All but one are still operating today.<ref>{{cite web | title = Roller Coaster Search Results, Title=Mine Train | url = http://www.rcdb.com/r.htm?ot=2&mo=8299 |accessdate = January 26, 2012}}</ref> Following almost four years of development, Toomer introduced the modern looping roller coaster in 1975 with the opening of ''[[Corkscrew (Silverwood)|Corkscrew]]'', the first in the world with two inversions, at [[Knott's Berry Farm]]. Knott's is credited with having the first, but three more identical coasters opened later that same year. The following year he introduced the familiar Arrow teardrop-shaped vertical loop on a custom corkscrew coaster at [[Cedar Point]] amusement park in Sandusky, Ohio.<ref name=AN/> At [[Cedar Point]] in 1989, Toomer unveiled the first roller coaster to top {{Convert|200|ft|m}} known as [[Magnum XL-200]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsplusnotes.blogspot.com/2011/09/arrow-legend-ron-toomer-passes-away.html|title=Arrow Legend Ron Toomer Passes Away|date=September 27, 2011|publisher=NewsPlusNotes|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, Arrow Development was purchased by [[Huss Maschinenfabrik]], which merged with Arrow Development to form Arrow-Huss. Toomer was made vice president and manager of engineering.<ref name=AN/> In 1986, 13 of the company's American officers negotiated a buyout, and formed Arrow Dynamics to which Toomer was named president.<ref name=AN/> In 1993 he was promoted to chairman of the board then became a consulting director in 1995. Toomer retired from Arrow Dynamics in 1998.<ref name=AN/>\n\nAlthough Toomer primarily designed coasters for Arrow, he also assisted with some of the other Arrow products, which included providing structural engineering for the company's Log Flumes.<ref name=AT/>\n\nA common misconception is that Ron Toomer never rode any of his rides. Although he did suffer from motion sickness, he would ride a coaster once, maybe twice. He was quoted as saying \"I've ridden enough to know what they are like.\"<ref name=AN/>\n\n==Notable Designs==\nRon Toomer's designs were highly innovative with many of his coasters breaking records. Notable designs include:\n\n* [[Runaway Mine Train (Six Flags Over Texas)]], first mine train type coaster.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Rush | first1 = Jan | year = 2007 | title = 100 Moments in Roller Coaster History: Runaway Mine Train | journal = RollerCoaster! Magazine | volume = 28 | issue = 2 | page = 18 | issn = 0896-7261}}</ref>\n* [[Corkscrew (Silverwood)|Roaring 20's Corkscrew]]<!--please do not change. This is the correct spelling of the coaster-->, ([[Knott's Berry Farm]]), first coaster with two inversions.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Scheinin | first1 = Lisa | year = 2007 | title = 100 Moments in Roller Coaster History: The First Corkscrew | journal = RollerCoaster! Magazine | volume = 28 | issue = 2 | page = 18 | issn = 0896-7261}}</ref>\n* [[Corkscrew (Cedar Point)]], first with three inversions.<ref name=RC98>{{cite journal | last1 = Seifert | first1 = Jeffrey | year = 2006 | title = Arrow | journal = RollerCoaster! Magazine | volume = 27 | issue = 4 | pages = 12\u201313 | issn = 0896-7261}}</ref>\n* [[Carolina Cyclone]] ([[Carowinds]]), first with four inversions.<ref name=RC98/>\n* Viper ([[Darien Lake]]), first with five inversions.<ref name=RC98/>\n* [[Vortex (Kings Island)]], first with six inversions.<ref name=RC98/>\n* [[Shockwave (Six Flags Great America)]], first with seven inversions.<ref name=RC98/>\n* Motorcycle Chase ([[Knott's Berry Farm]]), first modern-day steeplechase coaster.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Rush | first1 = Jan | year = 2007 | title = 100 Moments in Roller Coaster History: The First Modern Steeplechase Coaster | journal = RollerCoaster! Magazine | volume = 28 | issue = 2 | page = 19 | issn = 0896-7261}}</ref>\n* [[Loch Ness Monster (roller coaster)|Loch Ness Monster]] ([[Busch Gardens Williamsburg]]), first with interlocking vertical loops.<ref name=RC98/>\n* [[Orient Express (Worlds of Fun)]], introduced the Arrow Boomerang Element, originally called a Kamikaze Curve.<ref name=RC98/>\n* [[The Bat (Kings Island; opened 1981)|The Bat (Kings Island)]], prototype suspended coaster, although not the first suspended, it was the first in an amusement park.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Baldwin | first1 = Tim | year = 2006 | title = In Suspense, the Contemporary Suspended Coaster Celebrates a 25th Anniversary | journal = RollerCoaster! Magazine | volume = 27 | issue = 4 | pages = 15\u201319 | issn = 0896-7261}}</ref>\n* [[Gemini (roller coaster)|Gemini]] ([[Cedar Point]]), only Arrow racing coaster, record breaking height when opened.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Rush | first1 = Jan | year = 2007 | title = 100 Moments in Roller Coaster History: Gemini | journal = RollerCoaster! Magazine | volume = 28 | issue = 2 | page = 18 | issn = 0896-7261}}</ref>\n* [[Magnum XL-200]] ([[Cedar Point]]), first to exceed 200 feet.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Rueben | first1 = Paul | year = 2007 | title = 100 Moments in Roller Coaster History: Magnum XL-200 breaks the Height Barrier | journal = RollerCoaster! Magazine | volume = 28 | issue = 2 | page = 39 | issn = 0896-7261}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 2000 Ron Toomer was inducted into the IAAPA Hall of Fame as a Living Legend.<ref name=AN/>\n\nFour of Toomer's coasters have been designated Roller Coaster Landmarks by [[American Coaster Enthusiasts]]: [[Corkscrew (Silverwood)|Corkscrew]], [[Loch Ness Monster (roller coaster)|Loch Ness Monster]], [[Magnum XL-200]] and [[Runaway Mine Train (Six Flags Over Texas)|Run-A-Way Mine Train]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Coaster Landmark Awards | url = http://www.aceonline.org/CoasterAwards/?type=3 | accessdate = January 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*Website: http://www.iaapa.org/industry/funworld/2005/october05/Features/thrill_maker/thrill.html\n*PDF: http://amusementtoday.com/backissues/at_preiaapa_2011_web.pdf\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Toomer, Ron}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:Roller coaster designers]]\n[[Category:Amusement ride manufacturers]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Ron Toomer\n| image       =\n| alt         =\n| caption     =\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1930|05|31}}\n| birth_place = Pasadena, California\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|2011|09|26|1930|05|31}}\n| death_place = Bedford, Texas\n| nationality =\n| other_names =\n| known_for   = Arrow Dynamics\n| occupation  = Roller coaster designer\n}}\n'''Ron Toomer''' (birth name: '''Ronald Valentine Toomer''') (May 31, 1930&nbsp;\u2013 September 26, 2011)<ref>[http://www.amusementtoday.com/2011/09/26/industry-legend-ron-toomer-dies-at-81/ Industry legend Ron Toomer dies at 81]</ref> was an American [[roller coaster]] designer credited for designing 93 roller coasters around the world.<ref name=AT>{{Citation | last = Rutherford | first = Scott | title = Industry legend, roller coaster designer Ton Toomer dies at 81 | journal = Amusement Today | volume = 15 | issue = 8.1  | pages = 33\u201335  | date = November 2011}}</ref> He graduated from the [[University of Nevada, Reno]] in 1961 with a degree in mechanical engineering and was a part of the design team responsible for the [[Apollo program|Apollo]] spacecraft heat shield.<ref name=AT/>\n\n== Career ==\nRon Toomer was hired by [[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow Development]] founders Karl Bacon and Ed Morgan in 1965 to help design a mine train ride called [[Runaway Mine Train (Six Flags Over Texas)|Run-A-Way Mine Train]] at [[Six Flags Over Texas]].<ref name=AN>{{Citation | last = Seifert | first = Jeffrey | title = Ron Toomer 1930-2011  | journal = ACE News | volume = 24 | issue = 2 | page = 3 | date = December 2011}}</ref> It opened in 1966 utilizing the tubular steel rail technology that had been developed by Arrow for [[Disneyland]]'s [[Matterhorn Bobsleds]]. The concept caught on quickly and Toomer designed 15 more mine train coasters for Arrow. All but one are still operating today.<ref>{{cite web | title = Roller Coaster Search Results, Title=Mine Train | url = http://www.rcdb.com/r.htm?ot=2&mo=8299 |accessdate = January 26, 2012}}</ref> Following almost four years of development, Toomer introduced the modern looping roller coaster in 1975 with the opening of ''[[Corkscrew (Silverwood)|Corkscrew]]'', the first in the world with two inversions, at [[Knott's Berry Farm]]. Knott's is credited with having the first, but three more identical coasters opened later that same year. The following year he introduced the familiar Arrow teardrop-shaped vertical loop on a custom corkscrew coaster at [[Cedar Point]] amusement park in Sandusky, Ohio.<ref name=AN/> At [[Cedar Point]] in 1989, Toomer unveiled the first roller coaster to top {{Convert|200|ft|m}} known as [[Magnum XL-200]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsplusnotes.blogspot.com/2011/09/arrow-legend-ron-toomer-passes-away.html|title=Arrow Legend Ron Toomer Passes Away|date=September 27, 2011|publisher=NewsPlusNotes|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, Arrow Development was purchased by [[Huss Maschinenfabrik]], which merged with Arrow Development to form Arrow-Huss. Toomer was made vice president and manager of engineering.<ref name=AN/> In 1986, 13 of the company's American officers negotiated a buyout, and formed Arrow Dynamics to which Toomer was named president.<ref name=AN/> In 1993 he was promoted to chairman of the board then became a consulting director in 1995. Toomer retired from Arrow Dynamics in 1998.<ref name=AN/>\n\nAlthough Toomer primarily designed coasters for Arrow, he also assisted with some of the other Arrow products, which included providing structural engineering for the company's Log Flumes.<ref name=AT/>\n\nA common misconception is that Ron Toomer never rode any of his rides. Although he did suffer from motion sickness, he would ride a coaster once, maybe twice. He was quoted as saying \"I've ridden enough to know what they are like.\"<ref name=AN/>\n\n==Notable Designs==\nRon Toomer's designs were highly innovative with many of his coasters breaking records. Notable designs include:\n\n* [[Runaway Mine Train (Six Flags Over Texas)]], first mine train type coaster.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Rush | first1 = Jan | year = 2007 | title = 100 Moments in Roller Coaster History: Runaway Mine Train | journal = RollerCoaster! Magazine | volume = 28 | issue = 2 | page = 18 | issn = 0896-7261}}</ref>\n* [[Corkscrew (Silverwood)|Roaring 20's Corkscrew]]<!--please do not change. This is the correct spelling of the coaster-->, ([[Knott's Berry Farm]]), first coaster with two inversions.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Scheinin | first1 = Lisa | year = 2007 | title = 100 Moments in Roller Coaster History: The First Corkscrew | journal = RollerCoaster! Magazine | volume = 28 | issue = 2 | page = 18 | issn = 0896-7261}}</ref>\n* [[Corkscrew (Cedar Point)]], first with three inversions.<ref name=RC98>{{cite journal | last1 = Seifert | first1 = Jeffrey | year = 2006 | title = Arrow | journal = RollerCoaster! Magazine | volume = 27 | issue = 4 | pages = 12\u201313 | issn = 0896-7261}}</ref>\n* [[Carolina Cyclone]] ([[Carowinds]]), first with four inversions.<ref name=RC98/>\n* Viper ([[Darien Lake]]), first with five inversions.<ref name=RC98/>\n* [[Vortex (Kings Island)]], first with six inversions.<ref name=RC98/>\n* [[Shockwave (Six Flags Great America)]], first with seven inversions.<ref name=RC98/>\n* Motorcycle Chase ([[Knott's Berry Farm]]), first modern-day steeplechase coaster.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Rush | first1 = Jan | year = 2007 | title = 100 Moments in Roller Coaster History: The First Modern Steeplechase Coaster | journal = RollerCoaster! Magazine | volume = 28 | issue = 2 | page = 19 | issn = 0896-7261}}</ref>\n* [[Loch Ness Monster (roller coaster)|Loch Ness Monster]] ([[Busch Gardens Williamsburg]]), first with interlocking vertical loops.<ref name=RC98/>\n* [[Orient Express (Worlds of Fun)]], introduced the Arrow Boomerang Element, originally called a Kamikaze Curve.<ref name=RC98/>\n* [[The Bat (Kings Island; opened 1981)|The Bat (Kings Island)]], prototype suspended coaster, although not the first suspended, it was the first in an amusement park.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Baldwin | first1 = Tim | year = 2006 | title = In Suspense, the Contemporary Suspended Coaster Celebrates a 25th Anniversary | journal = RollerCoaster! Magazine | volume = 27 | issue = 4 | pages = 15\u201319 | issn = 0896-7261}}</ref>\n* [[Gemini (roller coaster)|Gemini]] ([[Cedar Point]]), only Arrow racing coaster, record breaking height when opened.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Rush | first1 = Jan | year = 2007 | title = 100 Moments in Roller Coaster History: Gemini | journal = RollerCoaster! Magazine | volume = 28 | issue = 2 | page = 18 | issn = 0896-7261}}</ref>\n* [[Magnum XL-200]] ([[Cedar Point]]), first to exceed 200 feet.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Rueben | first1 = Paul | year = 2007 | title = 100 Moments in Roller Coaster History: Magnum XL-200 breaks the Height Barrier | journal = RollerCoaster! Magazine | volume = 28 | issue = 2 | page = 39 | issn = 0896-7261}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 2000 Ron Toomer was inducted into the IAAPA Hall of Fame as a Living Legend.<ref name=AN/>\n\nFour of Toomer's coasters have been designated Roller Coaster Landmarks by [[American Coaster Enthusiasts]]: [[Corkscrew (Silverwood)|Corkscrew]], [[Loch Ness Monster (roller coaster)|Loch Ness Monster]], [[Magnum XL-200]] and [[Runaway Mine Train (Six Flags Over Texas)|Run-A-Way Mine Train]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Coaster Landmark Awards | url = http://www.aceonline.org/CoasterAwards/?type=3 | accessdate = January 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*Website: http://www.iaapa.org/industry/funworld/2005/october05/Features/thrill_maker/thrill.html\n*PDF: http://amusementtoday.com/backissues/at_preiaapa_2011_web.pdf\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Toomer, Ron}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:Roller coaster designers]]\n[[Category:Amusement ride manufacturers]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]