Single by Selena Gomez & the Scene (New Zealand)|work=iTunes|publisher=Apple, Inc|accessdate=2010-09-19}}</ref>\n|-\n|Portugal<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/pt/album/a-year-without-rain/id390870569?i=390870584&ign-mpt=uo%3D4|title=A Year Without Rain \u2013 Single by Selena Gomez & the Scene (Portugal)|work=iTunes|publisher=Apple, Inc|accessdate=2010-09-19}}</ref>\n|-\n|Spain<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/se/album/a-year-without-rain-single/id390870569|title=A Year Without Rain \u2013 Single by Selena Gomez & the Scene (Spain)|work=iTunes|publisher=Apple, Inc|accessdate=2010-09-19}}</ref>\n|-\n|Sweden<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/es/album/a-year-without-rain/id390870569?i=390870584&ign-mpt=uo%3D4|title=A Year Without Rain \u2013 Single by Selena Gomez & the Scene (Sweden)|work=iTunes|publisher=Apple, Inc|accessdate=2010-09-19}}</ref>\n|-\n|Switzerland<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/ch/album/a-year-without-rain/id390870569?i=390870584&ign-mpt=uo%3D4|title=A Year Without Rain \u2013 Single by Selena Gomez & the Scene (Switzerland)|work=iTunes|publisher=Apple, Inc|accessdate=2010-09-19}}</ref>\n|-\n|Germany<ref name=\"CD\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.de/dp/B0048IDRAK |title=A Year Without Rain \u2013 Single by Selena Gomez & the Scene (Germany)|publisher=[[Amazon.com|Amazon.de]]|language=German|accessdate=2010-10-24}}</ref>\n|November 12, 2010\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Compact Disc single|CD single]]\n|-\n|United Kingdom<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/B0048IDRAK/|title=A Year Without Rain: Selena Gomez|publisher=[[Amazon.com|Amazon.co.uk]]|accessdate=2011-11-13}}</ref>\n|November 22, 2010\n|-\n|Taiwan\n|October 24, 2010\n|[[Music download|Digital download]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*  [[List of number-one dance singles of 2011 (U.S.)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Selena Gomez & the Scene}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Year Without Rain (song)}}\n[[Category:2010 singles]]\n[[Category:Synth-pop ballads]]\n[[Category:Selena Gomez & the Scene songs]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Toby Gad]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Lindy Robbins]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Toby Gad]]\n[[Category:Eurodance songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Dance Club Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Hollywood Records singles]]\n[[Category:2010 songs]]\n[[Category:2010s ballads]]\n", "name_user": "2601:1c0:6902:64d0:9922:a36c:3abf:4824", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Year_Without_Rain_(song)"}
{"title_page": "Bradford City Radio", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2012}}\n'''Bradford City Radio''' or '''BCR''' as it was also known, was a small [[radio]] station in the early 1990s. It used the old [[Pennine Radio (radio station)|Pennine Radio]] frequency of 103.2 FM to broadcast.\n\nIts studios were based at Little Germany, just two minutes walk from Pennine Radio itself.<ref>http://www.mediauk.com/the_knowledge/i.muk/Bradford_City_Radio</ref>\n\nThe frequency is now used to [[Broadcasting|broadcast]] a local version of [[Sunrise Radio]] called [[Sunrise Radio (Yorkshire)]].\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Defunct radio stations in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Media in Bradford]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in Yorkshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2012}}\n'''Bradford City Radio''' or '''BCR''' as it was also known, was a small [[radio]] station in the early 90s. It used the old [[Pennine Radio (radio station)|Pennine Radio]] frequency of 103.2 FM to broadcast.\n\nIts studios were based at Little Germany, just two minutes walk from Pennine Radio itself.<ref>http://www.mediauk.com/the_knowledge/i.muk/Bradford_City_Radio</ref>\n\nThe frequency is now used to [[Broadcasting|broadcast]] a local version of [[Sunrise Radio]] called [[Sunrise Radio (Yorkshire)]].\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Defunct radio stations in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Media in Bradford]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in Yorkshire]]\n", "name_user": "Cyanolinguophile", "label": "safe", "comment": "single correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bradford_City_Radio"}
{"title_page": "The Dave Clark Five", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = The Dave Clark Five\n| background          = group_or_band\n| image               = Dave Clark Five 1964.JPG\n| caption             =\n| landscape           = yes\n| origin              = [[Tottenham]], [[London]], England\n| genre               = [[Rock and roll]], [[Pop music|pop]], [[Beat music|beat]]\n| years_active        = 1959\u20131970\n| label               = [[Columbia Graphophone Company|Columbia (EMI)]], [[Epic Records|Epic]], [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| associated_acts     =\n| current_members =\n| past_members        = [[Dave Clark (musician)|Dave Clark]]<br>[[Mike Smith (Dave Clark Five)|Mike Smith]] (deceased)<br>[[Lenny Davidson]]<br>[[Rick Huxley]] (deceased)<br>[[Denis Payton]] (deceased)\n| <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n}}\n'''The Dave Clark Five''', often called '''The DC5''', were an English [[rock and roll]] band formed in [[Tottenham]] in 1957. In January 1964 they had their first UK top ten single, \"[[Glad All Over]]\", which knocked [[the Beatles]]' \"[[I Want to Hold Your Hand]]\" off the top of the [[UK Singles Chart]]. It peaked at No. 6 in the United States in April 1964.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2008-03-06-dave-clark-five_N.htm|title=For Dave Clark Five, the accolades finally arrive |last=Gundersen|first=Edna|date=6 March 2008|accessdate=2010-07-13|publisher=Usatoday.com}}</ref> Although this was their only UK No. 1, they topped the US chart in December 1965, with their cover of Bobby Day's \"Over And Over\". Their version of [[Chet Powers]]' \"[[Get Together (The Youngbloods song)|Get Together]]\" reached No. 8 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] retitled as \"Everybody Get Together\".<ref>[http://musicvf.com/song.php?title=Everybody+Get+Together+by+The+Dave+Clark+Five&id=42326 The Dave Clark Five, \"Everybody Get Together\" chart position] Retrieved May 18, 2015</ref>\n\nThey were the second group of the [[British Invasion]] to appear on ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]'' in the United States (for two weeks in March 1964 following the Beatles' three weeks the previous month). They would ultimately have 13 appearances on the show. The group disbanded in early 1970. On 10 March 2008, the band was inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]].<ref name=RNR>{{cite web | title = Inductees for 2008 | url = http://www.rockhall.com/pressroom/2008-inductee-announcement/ | work = Rock and Roll Hall of Fame official website | date =  13 December 2007 | accessdate = 2008-03-11 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080201220931/http://www.rockhall.com/pressroom/2008-inductee-announcement/ |archivedate = 1 February 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Dave Clark Five 1966.JPG|thumb|''The Ed Sullivan Show'' in 1966. From left: Denis Payton, Dave Clark, Mike Smith, Rick Huxley and Lenny Davidson.]]\nThe band had its origins in 1958, as the backing musicians for [[north London]] vocalist Stan Saxon.<ref name=\"Larkin\">{{Cite book |last= |first= |authorlink= |editor1-first=Colin |editor1-last=Larkin |editor1-link=Colin Larkin (writer) |year=2011 |title=The Encyclopedia of Popular Music |edition=5th |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC |location=London |publisher=Omnibus Press |at=Clark, Dave, Five |isbn=9780857125958 }}</ref> [[Dave Clark (musician)|Dave Clark]] played drums and contributed background vocals, alongside a frequently changing lineup.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> Clark and guitarist [[Rick Huxley]] both participated in the 1958 lineup.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-21428486|title=Dave Clark Five bassist Huxley dies|date=12 February 2013|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref> Clark and his bandmates eventually split with Saxon and reconstituted themselves as a standalone concern in January 1962, making their home in the South Grove Youth Club in [[Tottenham]], London.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> After a little more evolution, a lasting ensemble was settled, with Clark on drums, Huxley moving to bass, [[Lenny Davidson]] on lead guitar, [[Denis Payton]] on saxophone (and harmonica and second guitar), and [[Mike Smith (Dave Clark Five)|Mike Smith]] on keyboards and main vocals.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/>  Davidson's previous bands were the Off Beats and the Impalas.<ref name=\"SkidRock\">{{cite web|url=http://www.skidmore.edu/~gthompso/britrock/60brchro/60brch40s.html |title=The Birth of a Nation |publisher=Skidmore.edu |date= |accessdate=2015-08-10}}</ref><ref name=rockhall/>\n\nThe DC5 was promoted as the vanguard of a \"Tottenham Sound\", a response to Liverpool's [[Mersey Beat]] sound.<ref name=\"Clark\">{{Cite book |last1=Clark |first1=Dick |authorlink1=Dick Clark |last2=Uslan |first2=Michael |authorlink2= |last3=Solomon |first3=Bruce |year=1981 |title=Dick Clark's the First 25 Years of Rock & Roll |location=New York |publisher=Dell Publishing |page=[https://archive.org/details/dickclarksfirst200usla/page/155 155] |isbn=044051763X |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/dickclarksfirst200usla/page/155 }}</ref> Dave Clark struck business deals that allowed him to produce the band's recordings and gave him control of the master recordings.<ref>James E. Perone, {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=S5UbIgKdAS4C&pg=PA91&dq=dave+clark+five#v=onepage&q=dave%20clark%20five&f=false |title=''Mods, rockers, and the music of the British invasion'' |page=94 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |year=2008 |isbn=978-0275998608 |accessdate=2010-07-13 }}</ref> Songwriting credits went to Clark, Clark and Smith, Clark and Davidson, and Clark and Payton although Ron Ryan actually wrote many of the songs. Session drummer [[Bobby Graham (musician)|Bobby Graham]] played, sometimes alongside Clark, on some of the band's hits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/bobby-graham-mn0001596254/biography|title=Bobby Graham &#124; Biography & History|website=AllMusic}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/bobby-graham-session-drummer-who-played-on-around-15000-records-1791653.html|title=Bobby Graham: Session drummer who played on around 15,000 records|date=23 September 2009|website=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nThe Dave Clark Five had 12 Top 40 hits in the UK between 1964 and 1967, and 17 records in the Top 40 of the US ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' chart. Their cover of [[Bobby Day]]'s \"[[Over and Over (Bobby Day song)|Over and Over]]\" went to No. 1 in the US on the [[Hot 100 No. 1 Hits of 1965 (USA)|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] on Christmas Day 1965, despite less impressive sales in the UK (it peaked at No. 45 on the [[UK Singles Chart]]). They made 18 appearances on ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]''<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=9xQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA160&dq=dave+clark+five#v=onepage&q=dave%20clark%20five&f=false |title= ''Orange Coast Magazine,'' Dec 1993 Vol. 19 No. 12 |issn=0279-0483 |publisher=Emmis Communications |accessdate=2010-07-13 |date= December 1993 }}</ref> \u2013 more than any [[British Invasion]] group.\n\nThe band released a film, ''[[Catch Us If You Can (film)|Catch Us If You Can]]'' (directed by [[John Boorman]]) in 1965. It starred [[Barbara Ferris]], and was released in the United States as ''Having a Wild Weekend''. The short film ''Hits in Action'' highlighted a series of Dave Clark Five hits.\n\nOther than the songs \"Inside and Out\", \"Maze of Love\" and \"Live in the Sky\", the band did not follow the [[psychedelic music]] trend.<ref>James E. Perone, {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=S5UbIgKdAS4C&pg=PA91&dq=dave+clark+five#v=onepage&q=dave%20clark%20five&f=false |title=''Mods, rockers, and the music of the British invasion'' |page=99|publisher=ABC-CLIO |year=2008 |isbn=978-0275998608 |accessdate=2010-07-13 }}</ref> The Dave Clark Five disbanded in 1970, having had three singles on the UK chart that year, two of which reached the Top Ten. In 1970, Davidson, Huxley and Payton left, and Alan Parker and Eric Ford joined on lead guitar and bass. That line-up, renamed \"Dave Clark & Friends\", lasted until 1972.\n\nBetween 1978 and 1993, none of their music was available to be purchased in any commercial format due to rights-holder Clark declining to license the band's recordings. In 1993, a single CD ''Glad All Over Again'' was produced by Dave himself and released by EMI in Britain.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.artistdirect.com/nad/store/artist/album/0,,3700098,00.html |title=Glad All Over Again CD Edition by The Dave Clark Five @ ARTISTdirect.com \u2013 Shop, Listen, Download |publisher=Artistdirect.com |accessdate=2010-07-13 }}</ref> After a 1989 deal with the Disney Channel to rebroadcast the 1960s ITV show ''[[Ready Steady Go!]]'' (which Clark owned), he made a deal with Disney-owned [[Hollywood Records]] to issue in 1993 a double CD ''History of the Dave Clark Five''.<ref name=Huf>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/harold-bronson/the-dave-clark-five-dave-_b_5091519.html | first=Harold | last=Bronson | date= 4 April 2014 |publisher= Huffington Post |title=The Dave Clark Five: Dave Clark's Miscalculation}}</ref>  No DC5 material was then legally available until 2008, when the 28-track ''Hits'' compilation was released by [[Universal Music]] in the UK. In 2009, selections from the band's catalogue were released on [[iTunes Store|iTunes]]. And in 2019, almost the entire catalogue from the band, including all the original 1960s studio albums, became available on [[Spotify]] for the first time.\n\n[[BMG Rights Management]], with whom Clark has recently joined forces to release the band's recordings, released a new DC5 greatest hits CD on 24 January 2020 in two configurations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bestclassicbands.com/dave-clark-five-hits-collection-bmg-12-3-19/|title=Dave Clark Five 'All the Hits' Collection Coming: Listen|website=Bestclassicbands.com|date=30 July 2017|accessdate=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Post break-up==\nDave Clark was also the band's manager and producer of their recordings. Following the group's break-up, Clark set up a media company.  In the process, he acquired the rights to the 1960s pop series ''[[Ready Steady Go!]]''. Additionally, he wrote and produced the 1986 London stage musical [[Time (musical)|''Time \u2013 The Musical'']] where he directed the last performance of Sir [[Laurence Olivier]]. A two-disc vinyl album was released in conjunction with the stage production featuring music recorded by [[Julian Lennon]] (singing DC5's song \"[[Because (The Dave Clark Five song)|Because]]\"), [[Freddie Mercury]], [[Stevie Wonder]], [[Cliff Richard]], [[Ashford & Simpson]] and Olivier's selected dialogue. This double album was digitally remastered and released on [[iTunes]] in May 2012.\n\n[[Mike Smith (Dave Clark Five)|Mike Smith]] teamed up with [[Mike d'Abo]] (previously with [[Manfred Mann]]) for one album in 1976. He also released a now-scarce CD in 2000 titled ''It's Only Rock & Roll'' and returned to performing in 2003 after a hiatus of 25 years. He formed Mike Smith's Rock Engine and did two mini-tours of the U.S. He died on 28 February 2008 in a [[Buckinghamshire]] hospital from pneumonia, a complication of a paralysing spinal injury sustained from a fall in 2003.<ref name=\"Smith obit\">{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7270242.stm |title=Dave Clark Five singer Smith dies |publisher=BBC |date=28 February 2008 |accessdate=2008-02-29}}</ref>\n\nDenis Payton died on 17 December 2006 at the age of 63 after a long battle with cancer.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2007/jan/05/guardianobituaries.obituaries1 |title=Denis Payton: Saxophonist who put the growl into the Dave Clark Five |author=Laing, Dave |date=5 January 2007 |website=[[TheGuardian.com]] |accessdate=29 May 2019 }}</ref> Rick Huxley died from emphysema on 11 February 2013 at the age of 72.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Rick Huxley, Bassist for the Dave Clark Five, Dies at 72 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/14/arts/music/rick-huxley-72-bassist-for-the-dave-clark-five.html |author= |date=14 February 2014 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=29 May 2019 |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] }}</ref> Lenny Davidson taught guitar for many years at a school in [[Cambridgeshire]], where he still lives.\n\n==Induction into Rock and Roll Hall of Fame==\nThe Dave Clark Five made the list of nominees for the class of 2008, and on 13 December 2007 it was announced that the band would be inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] on 10 March 2008.<ref name=\"RNR\"/> The group was inducted by [[Tom Hanks]], who wrote, directed and starred in the 1996 film ''[[That Thing You Do!]]'', which was about an American one-hit wonder band that became popular in the wake of the British Invasion.\n\nIn attendance with the three surviving members of the DC5 were the families of Lenny Davidson and Rick Huxley, and Denis Payton's two sons. Mike Smith had planned on attending but died eleven days before the induction. Dave Clark opened up his acceptance speech by saying that he felt like he was at the [[Academy Award|Oscars]]. Davidson's family mentioned that they arrived in New York City for the ceremony on 8 March, exactly 44 years after the group's first appearance on ''The Ed Sullivan Show''.\n\n[[Joan Jett]] honoured the Dave Clark Five by performing \"Bits and Pieces\" with John Mellencamp's band. To perform \"Glad All Over\", Jett was joined by [[John Fogerty]], [[John Mellencamp]], [[Billy Joel]] and other artists who performed throughout the evening.\n\n==Members==\nThe Dave Clark Five comprised:<ref name=\"SkidRock\"/>\n<!-- NB the date of birth \"1942\" or \"1939\" is disputed. Please refer to the discussion page before changing it here (mooncow) -->\n\n'''Classic lineup'''\n*[[Dave Clark (musician)|Dave Clark]] - backing and occasional lead vocals, drums (1959-1970; 1970\u20131972, Dave Clark and Friends spinoff group)<ref name=rockhall>{{cite web |url=http://www.rockhall.com/inductees/dave-clark-five  |title=The Dave Clark Five |publisher=The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and Museum |accessdate=2010-07-13}}</ref><ref name=tsimon>{{cite web |url=http://www.tsimon.com/dcfive.htm|title=Dave Clark Five|publisher=Tsimon.com|accessdate=2010-11-16 }}</ref>\n*[[Mike Smith (Dave Clark Five)|Mike Smith]] - lead vocals, keyboards (1961-1970; 1970\u20131973, Dave Clark and Friends spinoff group; died 2008)<ref name=rockhall/>\n*[[Lenny Davidson]] \u2013 backing and occasional lead vocals, lead and rhythm guitars (1961-1970)<ref name=rockhall/>\n*[[Rick Huxley]] (ex the Riverside Blues Boys, the Spon Valley Stompers) \u2013 backing vocals, bass guitar, rhythm guitar<ref name=rockhall/> (1959-1970; died 2013)\n*[[Denis Payton]] (ex the Renegades, the Les Heath Combo, the Blue Dukes, the Mike Jones Combo) \u2013 backing and occasional lead vocals, [[tenor saxophone|tenor]] and [[baritone saxophone]]s, harmonica, rhythm guitar (1962-1970; died 2006) <ref name=rockhall/><ref name=PaytonBBC>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6190357.stm |title=Entertainment &#124; Dave Clark Five star Payton dies |publisher=BBC News |date=2006-12-18 |accessdate=2015-08-10}}</ref>\n\n'''Early members'''\n* Stan Saxon - lead vocals, saxophone<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PgGqNrqfrsoC&pg=PP199&lpg=PP199&dq=stan+saxon+sax&source=bl&ots=cKEg7l8e8F&sig=ACfU3U0WmKBDYQEtmjMndxwfIevyamXhSA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiL09XshvPnAhVKc98KHVheBMEQ6AEwAnoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=stan+saxon+sax&f=false|title=The Billboard Book of Number One Hits|first=Fred|last=Bronson|date=11 March 2003|publisher=Billboard Books|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n* Mick Ryan - lead guitar<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* Chris Walls - bass<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n'''Dave Clark & Friends members'''\n* Alan Ford - lead guitar\n* Eric Parker - bass\n\n'''Timeline'''\n\n{{#tag:timeline|\nImageSize = width:800 height:auto barincrement:20\nPlotArea = left:100 bottom:90 top:15 right:15\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat  = dd/mm/yyyy\nPeriod = from:01/01/1958 till:01/01/1974\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nLegend = orientation:vertical position:bottom columns:4\nScaleMajor = increment:3 start:1958\nScaleMinor = increment:1 start:1958\n\nColors = \n id:vocals value:red         legend:Lead_and_backing_vocals\n id:v value:pink         legend:Backing_and_lead_vocals\n id:harm   value:gray(0.5)  legend:Harmonica\n id:sax value:yellow  legend:Saxophone\n id:lead value:teal       legend:Lead_guitar\n id:guitar value:brightgreen       legend: Rhythm_guitar\n id:keys   value:purple      legend:Keyboards\n id:bass   value:blue        legend:Bass\n id:drums  value:orange      legend:Drums,_percussion\n id:album  value:black       legend:Studio_album\n  id:bs value:gray(0.1)      \n  id:hh value:gray(0.3)\n\nBarData = \n  bar:band   text: \n bar:Mike text:\"Mike Smith\"\n bar:Dave text:\"Dave Clark\"\n bar:Lenny text:\"Lenny Davidson\"\n bar:Denis text:\"Denis Payton\"\n bar:Rick text:\"Rick Huxley\"\n bar:AlanParker text:\"Alan Parker\"\n bar:EricFord text:\"Eric Ford\"\n\n\nPlotData = \n align:center textcolor:white fontsize:7 width:15 shift:(2,-5)\n bar:band from:start till:01/01/1961 color:hh text:\"The Dave Clark Five feat. Stan Saxon\"\n bar:BAND from:01/01/1961 till:01/01/1971 color:bs text:\"The Dave Clark Five\"\n bar:band from:01/01/1971 till:end color:hh text:\"Dave Clark and Friends\"\n \n width:13\n bar:Mike from:01/01/1961 till:end color:vocals width:3\n bar:Mike from:01/01/1961     till:end color:keys\n\n bar:Dave from:start till:end color:drums\n bar:Dave from:start till:end color:v width:3\n\n bar:Lenny from:01/01/1961 till:01/01/1971 color:lead\n bar:Lenny from:01/01/1961 till:01/01/1967 color:v width:3\n bar:Lenny from:01/01/1967 till:01/01/1971 color:vocals width:3\n\n bar:Denis from:01/01/1962 till:01/01/1971 color:sax\n bar:Denis from:01/01/1962 till:01/01/1969 color:harm width:3\n bar:Denis from:01/01/1966 till:01/01/1969 color:guitar width:7\n bar:Denis from:01/01/1969 till:01/01/1971 color:guitar width:3\n\n bar:Rick from:01/01/1959 till:01/01/1961 color:guitar\n bar:Rick from:01/01/1961 till:01/01/1971 color:bass\n bar:Rick from:01/01/1962 till:01/01/1971 color:v width:3\n\n bar:AlanParker from:01/01/1971 till:end color:lead\n bar:EricFord from:01/01/1971 till:end color:bass\n\nLineData = \n color:album layer:back\n}}\n\n==Discography==\n{{Further|The Dave Clark Five discography}}\n\n'''Studio albums'''\n*''[[Glad All Over (Dave Clark Five album)|Glad All Over]]'' (US, 1964)\n*''[[The Dave Clark Five Return!]]'' (US, 1964) / ''[[A Session with The Dave Clark Five]]'' (UK, 1964)\n*''[[American Tour]]'' (US, 1964)\n*''[[Coast To Coast (Dave Clark Five album)|Coast to Coast]]'' (US, 1964)\n*''[[Weekend in London]]'' (US, 1965)\n*''Having a Wild Weekend'' (US, 1965) / ''Catch Us If You Can'' (UK, 1965)\n*''I Like It Like That'' (US, 1965)\n*''Try Too Hard'' (US, 1966)\n*''Satisfied with You'' (US, 1966)\n*''5 By 5'' (US, 1967)\n*''You Got What It Takes'' (US, 1967)\n*''Everybody Knows'' (UK, 1967) / ''Everybody Knows'' (US, 1968)\n*''5 by 5 = Go!'' (UK, 1969)\n*''If Somebody Loves You'' (UK, 1970)\n*''Good Old Rock'n'Roll'' (UK, 1971)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikipedia books|The Dave Clark Five}}\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q1141454|c=category:The Dave Clark Five|q=no|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|wikt=no|s=no}}\n*{{Official}}\n* [{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p3909|pure_url=yes}} Dave Clark Five biography at the Allmusic website].\n* {{Rockhall}}\n\n{{Dave Clark Five|state=expanded}}\n{{2008 Rock and Roll Hall of Fame}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dave Clark Five, The}}\n[[Category:The Dave Clark Five| ]]\n[[Category:Beat groups]]\n[[Category:British Invasion artists]]\n[[Category:English rock music groups]]\n[[Category:British rock and roll music groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from London]]\n[[Category:Musical quintets]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1957]]\n[[Category:1957 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 1970]]\n[[Category:1970 disestablishments in England]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records artists]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = The Dave Clark Five\n| background          = group_or_band\n| image               = Dave Clark Five 1964.JPG\n| caption             =\n| landscape           = yes\n| origin              = [[Tottenham]], [[London]], England\n| genre               = [[Rock and roll]], [[Pop music|pop]], [[Beat music|beat]]\n| years_active        = 1959\u20131970\n| label               = [[Columbia Graphophone Company|Columbia (EMI)]], [[Epic Records|Epic]], [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| associated_acts     =\n| current_members =\n| past_members        = [[Dave Clark (musician)|Dave Clark]]<br>[[Mike Smith (Dave Clark Five)|Mike Smith]] (deceased)<br>[[Lenny Davidson]]<br>[[Rick Huxley]] (deceased)<br>[[Denis Payton]] (deceased)\n| <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n}}\n'''The Dave Clark Five''', often called '''The DC5''', were an English [[rock and roll]] band formed in [[Tottenham]] in 1957. In January 1964 they had their first UK top ten single, \"[[Glad All Over]]\", which knocked [[the Beatles]]' \"[[I Want to Hold Your Hand]]\" off the top of the [[UK Singles Chart]]. It peaked at No. 6 in the United States in April 1964.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2008-03-06-dave-clark-five_N.htm|title=For Dave Clark Five, the accolades finally arrive |last=Gundersen|first=Edna|date=6 March 2008|accessdate=2010-07-13|publisher=Usatoday.com}}</ref> Although this was their only UK No. 1, they topped the US chart in December 1965, with their cover of Bobby Day's \"Over And Over\". Their version of [[Chet Powers]]' \"[[Get Together (The Youngbloods song)|Get Together]]\" reached No. 8 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] retitled as \"Everybody Get Together\".<ref>[http://musicvf.com/song.php?title=Everybody+Get+Together+by+The+Dave+Clark+Five&id=42326 The Dave Clark Five, \"Everybody Get Together\" chart position] Retrieved May 18, 2015</ref>\n\nThey were the second group of the [[British Invasion]] to appear on ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]'' in the United States (for two weeks in March 1964 following the Beatles' three weeks the previous month). They would ultimately have 13 appearances on the show. The group disbanded in early 1970. On 10 March 2008, the band was inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]].<ref name=RNR>{{cite web | title = Inductees for 2008 | url = http://www.rockhall.com/pressroom/2008-inductee-announcement/ | work = Rock and Roll Hall of Fame official website | date =  13 December 2007 | accessdate = 2008-03-11 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080201220931/http://www.rockhall.com/pressroom/2008-inductee-announcement/ |archivedate = 1 February 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Dave Clark Five 1966.JPG|thumb|''The Ed Sullivan Show'' in 1966. From left: Denis Payton, Dave Clark, Mike Smith, Rick Huxley and Lenny Davidson.]]\nThe band had its origins in 1958, as the backing musicians for [[north London]] vocalist Stan Saxon.<ref name=\"Larkin\">{{Cite book |last= |first= |authorlink= |editor1-first=Colin |editor1-last=Larkin |editor1-link=Colin Larkin (writer) |year=2011 |title=The Encyclopedia of Popular Music |edition=5th |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC |location=London |publisher=Omnibus Press |at=Clark, Dave, Five |isbn=9780857125958 }}</ref> [[Dave Clark (musician)|Dave Clark]] played drums and contributed background vocals, alongside a frequently changing lineup.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> Clark and guitarist [[Rick Huxley]] both participated in the 1958 lineup.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-21428486|title=Dave Clark Five bassist Huxley dies|date=12 February 2013|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref> Clark and his bandmates eventually split with Saxon and reconstituted themselves as a standalone concern in January 1962, making their home in the South Grove Youth Club in [[Tottenham]], London.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> After a little more evolution, a lasting ensemble was settled, with Clark on drums, Huxley moving to bass, [[Lenny Davidson]] on lead guitar, [[Denis Payton]] on saxophone (and harmonica and second guitar), and [[Mike Smith (Dave Clark Five)|Mike Smith]] on keyboards and main vocals.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/>  Davidson's previous bands were the Off Beats and the Impalas.<ref name=\"SkidRock\">{{cite web|url=http://www.skidmore.edu/~gthompso/britrock/60brchro/60brch40s.html |title=The Birth of a Nation |publisher=Skidmore.edu |date= |accessdate=2015-08-10}}</ref><ref name=rockhall/>\n\nThe DC5 was promoted as the vanguard of a \"Tottenham Sound\", a response to Liverpool's [[Mersey Beat]] sound.<ref name=\"Clark\">{{Cite book |last1=Clark |first1=Dick |authorlink1=Dick Clark |last2=Uslan |first2=Michael |authorlink2= |last3=Solomon |first3=Bruce |year=1981 |title=Dick Clark's the First 25 Years of Rock & Roll |location=New York |publisher=Dell Publishing |page=[https://archive.org/details/dickclarksfirst200usla/page/155 155] |isbn=044051763X |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/dickclarksfirst200usla/page/155 }}</ref> Dave Clark struck business deals that allowed him to produce the band's recordings and gave him control of the master recordings.<ref>James E. Perone, {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=S5UbIgKdAS4C&pg=PA91&dq=dave+clark+five#v=onepage&q=dave%20clark%20five&f=false |title=''Mods, rockers, and the music of the British invasion'' |page=94 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |year=2008 |isbn=978-0275998608 |accessdate=2010-07-13 }}</ref> Songwriting credits went to Clark, Clark and Smith, Clark and Davidson, and Clark and Payton although Ron Ryan actually wrote many of the songs. Session drummer [[Bobby Graham (musician)|Bobby Graham]] played, sometimes alongside Clark, on some of the band\u2019s hits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/bobby-graham-mn0001596254/biography|title=Bobby Graham &#124; Biography & History|website=AllMusic}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/bobby-graham-session-drummer-who-played-on-around-15000-records-1791653.html|title=Bobby Graham: Session drummer who played on around 15,000 records|date=23 September 2009|website=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nThe Dave Clark Five had 12 Top 40 hits in the UK between 1964 and 1967, and 17 records in the Top 40 of the US ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' chart. Their cover of [[Bobby Day]]'s \"[[Over and Over (Bobby Day song)|Over and Over]]\" went to No. 1 in the US on the [[Hot 100 No. 1 Hits of 1965 (USA)|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] on Christmas Day 1965, despite less impressive sales in the UK (it peaked at No. 45 on the [[UK Singles Chart]]). They made 18 appearances on ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]''<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=9xQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA160&dq=dave+clark+five#v=onepage&q=dave%20clark%20five&f=false |title= ''Orange Coast Magazine,'' Dec 1993 Vol. 19 No. 12 |issn=0279-0483 |publisher=Emmis Communications |accessdate=2010-07-13 |date= December 1993 }}</ref> \u2013 more than any [[British Invasion]] group.\n\nThe band released a film, ''[[Catch Us If You Can (film)|Catch Us If You Can]]'' (directed by [[John Boorman]]) in 1965. It starred [[Barbara Ferris]], and was released in the United States as ''Having a Wild Weekend''. The short film ''Hits in Action'' highlighted a series of Dave Clark Five hits.\n\nOther than the songs \"Inside and Out\", \"Maze of Love\" and \"Live in the Sky\", the band did not follow the [[psychedelic music]] trend.<ref>James E. Perone, {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=S5UbIgKdAS4C&pg=PA91&dq=dave+clark+five#v=onepage&q=dave%20clark%20five&f=false |title=''Mods, rockers, and the music of the British invasion'' |page=99|publisher=ABC-CLIO |year=2008 |isbn=978-0275998608 |accessdate=2010-07-13 }}</ref> The Dave Clark Five disbanded in 1970, having had three singles on the UK chart that year, two of which reached the Top Ten. In 1970, Davidson, Huxley and Payton left, and Alan Parker and Eric Ford joined on lead guitar and bass. That line-up, renamed \"Dave Clark & Friends\", lasted until 1972.\n\nBetween 1978 and 1993, none of their music was available to be purchased in any commercial format due to rights-holder Clark declining to license the band's recordings. In 1993, a single CD ''Glad All Over Again'' was produced by Dave himself and released by EMI in Britain.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.artistdirect.com/nad/store/artist/album/0,,3700098,00.html |title=Glad All Over Again CD Edition by The Dave Clark Five @ ARTISTdirect.com \u2013 Shop, Listen, Download |publisher=Artistdirect.com |accessdate=2010-07-13 }}</ref> After a 1989 deal with the Disney Channel to rebroadcast the 1960s ITV show ''[[Ready Steady Go!]]'' (which Clark owned), he made a deal with Disney-owned [[Hollywood Records]] to issue in 1993 a double CD ''History of the Dave Clark Five''.<ref name=Huf>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/harold-bronson/the-dave-clark-five-dave-_b_5091519.html | first=Harold | last=Bronson | date= 4 April 2014 |publisher= Huffington Post |title=The Dave Clark Five: Dave Clark's Miscalculation}}</ref>  No DC5 material was then legally available until 2008, when the 28-track ''Hits'' compilation was released by [[Universal Music]] in the UK. In 2009, selections from the band's catalogue were released on [[iTunes Store|iTunes]]. And in 2019, almost the entire catalogue from the band, including all the original 1960s studio albums, became available on [[Spotify]] for the first time.\n\n[[BMG Rights Management]], with whom Clark has recently joined forces to release the band's recordings, released a new DC5 greatest hits CD on 24 January 2020 in two configurations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bestclassicbands.com/dave-clark-five-hits-collection-bmg-12-3-19/|title=Dave Clark Five 'All the Hits' Collection Coming: Listen|website=Bestclassicbands.com|date=30 July 2017|accessdate=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Post break-up==\nDave Clark was also the band's manager and producer of their recordings. Following the group's break-up, Clark set up a media company.  In the process, he acquired the rights to the 1960s pop series ''[[Ready Steady Go!]]''. Additionally, he wrote and produced the 1986 London stage musical [[Time (musical)|''Time \u2013 The Musical'']] where he directed the last performance of Sir [[Laurence Olivier]]. A two-disc vinyl album was released in conjunction with the stage production featuring music recorded by [[Julian Lennon]] (singing DC5's song \"[[Because (The Dave Clark Five song)|Because]]\"), [[Freddie Mercury]], [[Stevie Wonder]], [[Cliff Richard]], [[Ashford & Simpson]] and Olivier's selected dialogue. This double album was digitally remastered and released on [[iTunes]] in May 2012.\n\n[[Mike Smith (Dave Clark Five)|Mike Smith]] teamed up with [[Mike d'Abo]] (previously with [[Manfred Mann]]) for one album in 1976. He also released a now-scarce CD in 2000 titled ''It's Only Rock & Roll'' and returned to performing in 2003 after a hiatus of 25 years. He formed Mike Smith's Rock Engine and did two mini-tours of the U.S. He died on 28 February 2008 in a [[Buckinghamshire]] hospital from pneumonia, a complication of a paralysing spinal injury sustained from a fall in 2003.<ref name=\"Smith obit\">{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7270242.stm |title=Dave Clark Five singer Smith dies |publisher=BBC |date=28 February 2008 |accessdate=2008-02-29}}</ref>\n\nDenis Payton died on 17 December 2006 at the age of 63 after a long battle with cancer.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2007/jan/05/guardianobituaries.obituaries1 |title=Denis Payton: Saxophonist who put the growl into the Dave Clark Five |author=Laing, Dave |date=5 January 2007 |website=[[TheGuardian.com]] |accessdate=29 May 2019 }}</ref> Rick Huxley died from emphysema on 11 February 2013 at the age of 72.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Rick Huxley, Bassist for the Dave Clark Five, Dies at 72 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/14/arts/music/rick-huxley-72-bassist-for-the-dave-clark-five.html |author= |date=14 February 2014 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=29 May 2019 |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] }}</ref> Lenny Davidson taught guitar for many years at a school in [[Cambridgeshire]], where he still lives.\n\n==Induction into Rock and Roll Hall of Fame==\nThe Dave Clark Five made the list of nominees for the class of 2008, and on 13 December 2007 it was announced that the band would be inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] on 10 March 2008.<ref name=\"RNR\"/> The group was inducted by [[Tom Hanks]], who wrote, directed and starred in the 1996 film ''[[That Thing You Do!]]'', which was about an American one-hit wonder band that became popular in the wake of the British Invasion.\n\nIn attendance with the three surviving members of the DC5 were the families of Lenny Davidson and Rick Huxley, and Denis Payton's two sons. Mike Smith had planned on attending but died eleven days before the induction. Dave Clark opened up his acceptance speech by saying that he felt like he was at the [[Academy Award|Oscars]]. Davidson's family mentioned that they arrived in New York City for the ceremony on 8 March, exactly 44 years after the group's first appearance on ''The Ed Sullivan Show''.\n\n[[Joan Jett]] honoured the Dave Clark Five by performing \"Bits and Pieces\" with John Mellencamp's band. To perform \"Glad All Over\", Jett was joined by [[John Fogerty]], [[John Mellencamp]], [[Billy Joel]] and other artists who performed throughout the evening.\n\n==Members==\nThe Dave Clark Five comprised:<ref name=\"SkidRock\"/>\n<!-- NB the date of birth \"1942\" or \"1939\" is disputed. Please refer to the discussion page before changing it here (mooncow) -->\n\n'''Classic lineup'''\n*[[Dave Clark (musician)|Dave Clark]] - backing and occasional lead vocals, drums (1959-1970; 1970-1972, Dave Clark and Friends spinoff group)<ref name=rockhall>{{cite web |url=http://www.rockhall.com/inductees/dave-clark-five  |title=The Dave Clark Five |publisher=The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and Museum |accessdate=2010-07-13}}</ref><ref name=tsimon>{{cite web |url=http://www.tsimon.com/dcfive.htm|title=Dave Clark Five|publisher=Tsimon.com|accessdate=2010-11-16 }}</ref>\n*[[Mike Smith (Dave Clark Five)|Mike Smith]] - lead vocals, keyboards (1961-1970; 1970-1973, Dave Clark and Friends spinoff group; died 2008)<ref name=rockhall/>\n*[[Lenny Davidson]] \u2013 backing and occasional lead vocals, lead and rhythm guitars (1961-1970)<ref name=rockhall/>\n*[[Rick Huxley]] (ex the Riverside Blues Boys, the Spon Valley Stompers) \u2013 backing vocals, bass guitar, rhythm guitar<ref name=rockhall/> (1959-1970; died 2013)\n*[[Denis Payton]] (ex the Renegades, the Les Heath Combo, the Blue Dukes, the Mike Jones Combo) \u2013 backing and occasional lead vocals, [[tenor saxophone|tenor]] and [[baritone saxophone]]s, harmonica, rhythm guitar (1962-1970; died 2006) <ref name=rockhall/><ref name=PaytonBBC>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6190357.stm |title=Entertainment &#124; Dave Clark Five star Payton dies |publisher=BBC News |date=2006-12-18 |accessdate=2015-08-10}}</ref>\n\n'''Early members'''\n* Stan Saxon - lead vocals, saxophone<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PgGqNrqfrsoC&pg=PP199&lpg=PP199&dq=stan+saxon+sax&source=bl&ots=cKEg7l8e8F&sig=ACfU3U0WmKBDYQEtmjMndxwfIevyamXhSA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiL09XshvPnAhVKc98KHVheBMEQ6AEwAnoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=stan+saxon+sax&f=false|title=The Billboard Book of Number One Hits|first=Fred|last=Bronson|date=11 March 2003|publisher=Billboard Books|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n* Mick Ryan - lead guitar<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* Chris Walls - bass<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n'''Dave Clark & Friends members'''\n* Alan Ford - lead guitar\n* Eric Parker - bass\n\n'''Timeline'''\n\n{{#tag:timeline|\nImageSize = width:800 height:auto barincrement:20\nPlotArea = left:100 bottom:90 top:15 right:15\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat  = dd/mm/yyyy\nPeriod = from:01/01/1958 till:01/01/1974\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nLegend = orientation:vertical position:bottom columns:4\nScaleMajor = increment:3 start:1958\nScaleMinor = increment:1 start:1958\n\nColors = \n id:vocals value:red         legend:Lead_and_backing_vocals\n id:v value:pink         legend:Backing_and_lead_vocals\n id:harm   value:gray(0.5)  legend:Harmonica\n id:sax value:yellow  legend:Saxophone\n id:lead value:teal       legend:Lead_guitar\n id:guitar value:brightgreen       legend: Rhythm_guitar\n id:keys   value:purple      legend:Keyboards\n id:bass   value:blue        legend:Bass\n id:drums  value:orange      legend:Drums,_percussion\n id:album  value:black       legend:Studio_album\n  id:bs value:gray(0.1)      \n  id:hh value:gray(0.3)\n\nBarData = \n  bar:band   text: \n bar:Mike text:\"Mike Smith\"\n bar:Dave text:\"Dave Clark\"\n bar:Lenny text:\"Lenny Davidson\"\n bar:Denis text:\"Denis Payton\"\n bar:Rick text:\"Rick Huxley\"\n bar:AlanParker text:\"Alan Parker\"\n bar:EricFord text:\"Eric Ford\"\n\n\nPlotData = \n align:center textcolor:white fontsize:7 width:15 shift:(2,-5)\n bar:band from:start till:01/01/1961 color:hh text:\"The Dave Clark Five feat. Stan Saxon\"\n bar:BAND from:01/01/1961 till:01/01/1971 color:bs text:\"The Dave Clark Five\"\n bar:band from:01/01/1971 till:end color:hh text:\"Dave Clark and Friends\"\n \n width:13\n bar:Mike from:01/01/1961